        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1980080472" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17605119262616954475">This book was incredible. I had only vaguely heard about it and needed something new to audiobook, and wound up having my mind blown. <br/><br/>It&apos;s a story of the opioid epidemic told through fascinating characters and a history of capitalism over the past few decades--everything from the disappearance of factory jobs to the retailing of heroin sales to the birth of pharma advertising to the role of Walmart in small towns and so much more. <br/><br/>It occasionally slides into some sort of weird bootstrappy ish wh</span>
  <span id="freeText17605119262616954475" style="display:none">This book was incredible. I had only vaguely heard about it and needed something new to audiobook, and wound up having my mind blown. <br /><br />It's a story of the opioid epidemic told through fascinating characters and a history of capitalism over the past few decades--everything from the disappearance of factory jobs to the retailing of heroin sales to the birth of pharma advertising to the role of Walmart in small towns and so much more. <br /><br />It occasionally slides into some sort of weird bootstrappy ish when talking about alternatives to opioid prescriptions for chronic pain, but it's such an amazing work of journalism that I'll forgive the author not being a commie like me. Because it turns out, when you do in-depth journalism of this magnitude, you do wind up at the conclusion that it's the "free market" at fault. <br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="17605119262616954475" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
